
Church's thesis states that every computation can be encoded as a
PURE lambda-term. We hereby pay homage to Church's thesis by showing
that the extensions (so far) added to LAMBDA can be translated into
PURE lambda-calculus.

############################################################
# datatype term =
# | TMint of sint
# | TMbtf of bool
# | TMvar of strn(*name*) // name
# | TMlam of (strn, term) // abstraction
# | TMapp of (term, term) // application
# | TMop2 of (strn(*name*), term(*arg1*), term(*arg2))
# | TMifb of (term(*cond*), term(*then*), term(*else*))
############################################################

In particular, you are asked to translate TMint, TMbtf, TMop2, and TMifb
into Church's pure lambda-calculus.

######
#
# Task 1
#
######

def TMint_trans(tm0):
  assert tm0.ctag == "TMint"
  # HX: 10 points
  # Please write code that generates the Church numeral
  # for tm0.arg1 (which is assumed to be a non-negative
  # integer)

def TMbtf_trans(tm0):
  assert tm0.ctag == "TMbtf"
  # HX: 10 points
  # Please write code that generates the Church boolean
  # for tm0.arg1 (which is either True or False)
  #

def TMop2_trans(tm0):
  assert tm0.ctag == "TMop2"
  #
  # HX: 100 points
  # This is the most interesting part
  # You only need to handle: +, -, *
  # You only need to handle: <, <=, >, >=, ==, and !=
  #

def TMifb_trans(tm0):
  assert tm0.ctag == "TMifb"
  #
  # HX: 10 points
  # Please translate 'TMifb' into the pure lambda-calc
  #

